align=left class=m><span class=title> Ogre Roleplaying Guide</span><hr size=1> This is the beginnings of an Oger RP guide that I've been working up, haven't really gotten into the Language part yet.  Any comments, praise, criticism, etc. would be welcomed.<br>
<br>
&gt; Ogers an' der Waez. <br>
&gt; bi: Ghuarboktumawg <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Ogers are a race that somehow manages to maintain a sense of <br>
innocence throughout their entire lives. This is accomplished by the <br>
fact that most Ogres never develop past the point of what, for a <br>
human, would be the age of six or seven. Ogres remain childish and <br>
immature throughout their entire lives. As a result of this, they <br>
often display many of the following characteristics. <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Overconfidence - Like most children, Ogres know everything, or <br>
think they do. They are happy to tell anyone about it, as they feel <br>
they are speaking from a position of immense knowledge of just about <br>
any subject. <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Questioning and Gullibility - Also, like Children, Ogres are very <br>
inquisitive about things which they have not encountered before and <br>
are likely to ask a multitude of questions about any new object they <br>
discover ie &quot;Is dis gud ta eet?&quot;, &quot;Wud is gud ta drink wif dis wen me <br>
eets it?&quot; &quot;Does me barsh it, or pokee it?&quot;, etc. They are also very <br>
trusting of the answers they receive to their queries. To this day <br>
many Ogres still believe that ice cream comes from frozen cows, and <br>
chocolate milk from brown ones. <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Self-Centered - Ogres, like children, enjoy attention, some crave <br>
it and go out of their way to get it, others simply relish it when <br>
they get it. Any time an Ogre is being payed close attention to he <br>
will go out of his way to be impressive, using larger words than he <br>
can handle, and trying to bash things well beyond his or her <br>
capabilities, often reinforcing the smaller races view that Ogres are <br>
stupid. For instance, Mawg speaks in rhyme as much as possible, <br>
trying to prove himself to be smarter than the goblins and in hopes <br>
of earning praise, love, and attention from his guildmates and group <br>
members. <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Lack of Time Sense - Ogres are creatures of the present moment, <br>
having little ability to adequately comprehend the concepts of before <br>
and after. This is partly because Ogres are ruled by their stomachs <br>
and partly because of their lack of mental development. As such, <br>
most Ogres have no real distinctions when it comes to the tense of <br>
the verbs they use. Ogres can speak in the past, present, and future <br>
tenses about the same event, and although they understand each other, <br>
they tend to confuse the smaller races, continuing the Ogres views <br>
that the small races can be &quot;Jus' as 'toopid.&quot; <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Numbers - Ogre development usually starts just short of the point <br>
where the other races begin to be able to handle abstract numbers. <br>
Thus Ogres have difficult times with the concepts of one, two, three, <br>
etc. Ogres, instead, use their bodies as counting devices, using <br>
fingers, and toes as a more solid representation of numbers. For <br>
instance, the number four becomes &quot;Finger, Finger, Finger, Finger.&quot;, <br>
the number 16 would become &quot;Hand, Hand, Foot, Toe.&quot; and 22 would <br>
be &quot;Oger(20 digist on an oger), Finger, Finger.&quot; <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Evil - Ogres are not really evil, at least not in general. Ogres <br>
are relatively simple people, mainly absorbed with bashing things and <br>
eating them in order to maintain their great bulks. While this may <br>
seem evil to many races, it isn't, there is no malice or real <br>
rational thought behind the Ogre's drive for food, it is meerly <br>
instinctive. Ogres are not really good either, they are mainly <br>
innocents. They may turn one way or another based upon their <br>
teachings though. Remember, Ogres are highly gullible, and usually <br>
whichever side gets to them first can win them over with a few treats <br>
and lectures on their point of view. Of course, most of the good <br>
races are too foolish to see this and would rather kill Ogres because <br>
of their dietary habits than to raise them. <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Single Perspective - Ogres are unable to look at things from <br>
anything other than their own perspective, most of the time. If an <br>
Ogre is feeling hungry (which is almost always) he will not be able <br>
to understand the fact that noone else is hungry. Ogres are also <br>
unable to understand the fact that something that sounds perfectly <br>
normal to them may sound like gibberish to someone else, this tends <br>
to lead to frustration on both sides occasionally. Also, Ogres have <br>
trouble understanding why anyone would dislike them when they like <br>
themselves. <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; Lack of Connections - Ogres have trouble remembering connections <br>
between things. An Ogre may kill Trolls until they hate him, but <br>
then two days later will be unable to figure out why the Trolls have <br>
suddenly decided to start hunting him. This can certainly lead to <br>
problems, as Ogres will not remember that the same creature &quot;Barshed <br>
dem gud,&quot; only two days ago and may repeat the same mistake and <br>
getting beat up again. <br>
&gt; <br>
&gt; That's it for the moment. Remember, Ogres are basically just half- <br>
ton children with little real ability to comprehend their own safety <br>
or that of their group. Each Ogre should have his or her own <br>
special, unique querks and mannerisms, otherwise, just try to think <br>
like you did when you were 5 or 6 and you should do fine. <br>
